WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.520
 So now we're gonna take a look at the code

00:00:02.520 --> 00:00:04.640
 that actually writes the views,

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:07.980
 the code effectively in views dot py.

00:00:07.980 --> 00:00:10.960
 Now the first view that we're gonna take a look at

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:13.520
 is one where we're not even writing any code at all,

00:00:13.520 --> 00:00:17.120
 and this is that predefined view, that template view.

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:20.400
 And again, template view is code that a class

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:25.400
 that's given to us from django, template view,

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:27.600
 and you pass it a parameter,

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:29.920
 so we're actually kind of calling a function here,

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:32.800
 and passing a template name to it,

00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:37.060
 and that is a file, views, main.html.

00:00:37.060 --> 00:00:39.760
 So this is the application views,

00:00:39.760 --> 00:00:41.840
 there's a subfolder called templates,

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:43.680
 and then I'll talk about this in a bit,

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:45.840
 we repeat the application name twice,

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:47.520
 so that's a little bit weird,

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:49.800
 but it has to do with the fact that these names

00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:53.800
 are global across all of the applications,

00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:56.480
 and so you want there to be possibly

00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:58.760
 more than one main.html,

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:01.760
 and so that's why you have this extra folder name,

00:01:01.760 --> 00:01:04.980
 and you put this there, even though that feels

00:01:04.980 --> 00:01:07.440
 a little bit redundant, but it's okay.

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:11.560
 And so this is just a static HTML file,

00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:13.760
 I'm not gonna read any data from a database,

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:16.160
 I'm not gonna write any data to the database,

00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:17.620
 I'm just gonna read this file

00:01:17.620 --> 00:01:19.600
 and send it back to the browser,

00:01:19.600 --> 00:01:21.960
 and that's a common thing, where we just have a file

00:01:21.960 --> 00:01:23.840
 that we wanna send back to the browser,

00:01:23.840 --> 00:01:27.000
 and so we just don't even have to write any Python code

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.800
 other than add this entry into the URL patterns

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:34.960
 in urls.py, so that's a view where you wrote no Python code.

00:01:34.960 --> 00:01:38.160
 Now, for the parts where you're gonna write Python code

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:42.000
 for a view, you're gonna be passed in variables,

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.720
 the variables are all about the request object,

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:47.440
 the request object is all the data coming in,

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:51.000
 and the response object is something you produce in the view,

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:52.800
 and you send it all back.

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:57.000
 So, the request object is an object instance

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.800
 of class HTTP request, this is a predefined Django,

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:03.080
 and there's just a whole bunch of things.

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:05.280
 The scheme, now what is the scheme?

00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:08.120
 Whether or not it's secure or insecure HTTPS,

00:02:08.120 --> 00:02:10.180
 the body, it's a string.

00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:13.920
 So, there's like about 20 or 30 attributes,

00:02:13.920 --> 00:02:15.420
 we're gonna use some of them,

00:02:15.420 --> 00:02:16.680
 but you don't have to use all of them,

00:02:16.680 --> 00:02:18.960
 but you can go look up the documentation,

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:21.400
 and the more sophisticated your application becomes,

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:23.240
 the more likely you're gonna have to go digging in

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:26.040
 to find some little bit of the incoming request.

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:28.560
 You could think of this request data

00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:32.720
 as all that data you see in your browser debugger,

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:34.520
 about what data was sent to the server,

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:37.520
 that all ends up somewhere in this object.

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:40.600
 Now, when we return from a view,

00:02:40.600 --> 00:02:42.760
 we have to send a response back,

00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:44.680
 and so the response is something

00:02:44.680 --> 00:02:47.240
 that we create inside of our view,

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:49.800
 it might be simply text that's HTML,

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:52.400
 or it might be a redirect object,

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:55.680
 redirect response that says, hey, go to a different page.

00:02:55.680 --> 00:03:00.120
 And so, we make that, the main job at the end of the view

00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:01.680
 is to produce a response,

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:03.420
 and then return it back to Django.

00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:08.600
 And so, here is a very simple view.

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:12.680
 So, here we're saying, you know,

00:03:12.680 --> 00:03:14.120
 we're in the views application,

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:16.360
 we're gonna go to the view funky, right?

00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:21.360
 And so, in the URLs PY, we say map/funky

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:26.400
 to this function named funky.

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:31.040
 It's a funky function, that's why I call it funky.

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:34.880
 And so, when it sees this,

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:36.800
 all the data coming into the request

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:38.720
 shows up in this variable,

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:41.880
 that is the first parameter sent to that function.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:45.680
 So, that's what this is saying in URLs.PY.

00:03:45.680 --> 00:03:49.320
 Take everything that goes to view/funky,

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:52.240
 gather up all the request data from the browser,

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:56.020
 put it in an object, and then pass that request object in.

00:03:56.020 --> 00:04:00.280
 Now, in this, I'm not really going to do anything

00:04:00.280 --> 00:04:02.000
 with that request object,

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.880
 because I'm always returning the exact same thing.

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:07.760
 And so, I just have a nice triple quoted string

00:04:07.760 --> 00:04:10.580
 and some HTML with less than's and greater than's,

00:04:10.580 --> 00:04:13.480
 and I'm going to basically return,

00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:16.920
 it is my job in the view to give back a response.

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:19.040
 There's a couple, two main types of them,

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:20.640
 one is an HTTP response,

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:23.480
 which is just like a body of text,

00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:24.640
 and that's what I'm sending here.

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:28.040
 I'm sending an HTTP response, that's a constructor,

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:30.680
 we're constructing an HTTP response object,

00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:33.760
 and taking that string that I put in there,

00:04:33.760 --> 00:04:35.560
 and away we go, okay?

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:39.460
 And so, that basically, if you hit this path,

00:04:39.460 --> 00:04:41.760
 you're gonna get this page back,

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:45.960
 and it sort of looks like that when it's all said and done.

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:48.060
 Okay, so now, we want to talk about

00:04:48.060 --> 00:04:49.960
 how we can get at parameters.

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:52.280
 So, I mentioned that this request object

00:04:52.280 --> 00:04:54.920
 that comes in to your view function

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:57.100
 has all the data from the request.

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:02.100
 Well, if we send to a view with this question mark,

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:06.760
 key value pairs, that's guess equals 42 on there,

00:05:06.760 --> 00:05:09.320
 and we're gonna route danger to views.danger

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:14.260
 and urls.py, and so all this data is wrapped up

00:05:14.260 --> 00:05:16.560
 in this variable called request,

00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:19.040
 passed into the function named danger.

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:23.440
 And so, inside of request is some data.

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:28.440
 Request.GET is a dictionary of the key value pairs

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:32.360
 that are on that URL.

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:37.360
 So, to pull the 42 out, we can say request.get bracket,

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:41.240
 quote, guess, quote, and that pulls that out.

00:05:41.240 --> 00:05:42.680
 And so, that's all we've got here

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:44.720
 is a really simple HTML page,

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:48.520
 and we are replacing that little chunk with 42.

00:05:48.520 --> 00:05:51.720
 And so, whatever this number is comes back out

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:55.460
 in the output, so your guess was 42.

00:05:55.460 --> 00:05:59.920
 So, that's how we pass get data into a view.

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:04.240
 Now, up next, I'm gonna explain to you

00:06:04.240 --> 00:06:08.740
 exactly why it is I called that function danger.

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:11.320
 (upbeat music)

